article.description:
Alana Beard scored 21 points and DeLisha Milton-Jones added 19
as the Washington Mystics beat the Indiana Fever 74-67.
article.headline: Fever clinch playoff berth despite loss to Mystics
article.linkText: Fever clinch playoff berth despite loss to Mystics
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Although the Indiana Fever clinched a
playoff berth, the Washington Mystics looked more postseason-ready.

Alana Beard scored 21 points and DeLisha Milton-Jones added 19
as Washington beat Indiana 74-67.

Despite the loss, the Fever clinched a playoff berth with New
York's 85-80 win over Charlotte. It's the third playoff berth in
Indiana's seven-year history and its second in a row.

Washington stands a good chance of earning a playoff spot as
well, and the Mystics considered winning a road game against a
playoff team a major accomplishment.

"You could tell by the spirit and exuberance when we got into
the locker room," Washington coach Richie Adubato said.

Tan White scored 18 points for the Fever (16-10) and Tamika
Catchings had 17 points, six rebounds, six assists and six steals.

Indiana finished 3-2 on its critical five-game homestand.
Saturday's loss was disappointing after the Fever beat defending
WNBA champion Sacramento 75-60 on Tuesday.

"I can't explain tonight's game," Fever coach Brian Winters
said. "I'm not thinking of the playoffs right now, I'm only
thinking of Chicago tomorrow. We must take care of our own
business. We didn't tonight."

The Mystics tested Indiana's reputation as a poor perimeter
shooting team by playing zone defense for much of the game. The
Fever shot 41 percent overall and 33 percent from 3-point range.

Washington starters Crystal Robinson and Nikki Teasley left the
game with injuries in the first quarter and didn't play again.
Robinson turned an ankle but could have returned if necessary.
Teasley fell on a layup and was on the bench with a hot pack on her
back in the second half.

Despite being shorthanded, the Mystics (14-13) closed the first
quarter on a 12-0 run to take a 20-10 lead.

Washington continued to shoot well in the second quarter. The
Mystics took a 37-22 lead with 40 seconds to go in the first half
before Indiana's Anna DeForge made a layup with one second left.

Washington forced 11 turnovers in the first half and held the
Fever to 38 percent shooting.

Milton-Jones scored 11 points in the third quarter to help the
Mystics build a 19-point lead, but Indiana closed the quarter on a
7-2 run to cut Washington's lead to 56-42.

Indiana's Tamika Whitmore scored four quick points early in the
fourth quarter to trim Washington's lead to 57-46 and force a
timeout.

A flagrant foul on Milton-Jones with 8:30 left gave Indiana a
chance to draw closer. Catchings, who was fouled, made the second
of two free throws. White made a 3-pointer on the extra possession
to make it a 57-50 game with 8:17 remaining.

Milton-Jones responded with five quick points to bump
Washington's lead back to 62-51, and the Mystics maintained control
from there.

"This was the first complete game we've played all season,"
Milton-Jones said. "Usually, we have lapses in the third and
fourth quarters that cause us to lose leads and lose games.
Tonight, we sustained the lead throughout the game."

Now the Mystics, who have trailed Connecticut, Detroit and
Indiana in the East all season, are 2½ games behind the third-place
Fever with seven games left.

"We're right behind them, and we haven't been able to win here
in the past," Adubato said. "It's a confidence builder."
